---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="The Rule · Kit & Caliber"
  description="Two objects, one honest reason they belong together that has nothing to do with how they photograph."
>
  <section class="hero">
    <div class="wrap">
      <div class="eyebrow">
        <span class="no">THE RULE</span>
        <span class="mono">What this is, in one page</span>
      </div>

      <h1 class="rule-title">Two objects.<br />One question.<br />One reason.</h1>

      <p class="verdict-lead">
        A pairing earns its place when two things answer the same question, and the
        answer has nothing to do with how they photograph. What the two objects are
        matters less than whether the reason holds.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <article class="article">
    <div class="wrap">
      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          This is not a review site. Nobody here is going to tell you the water
          resistance rating or the zero-to-sixty time, because those numbers already
          exist everywhere and they were never the point. What you get instead is an
          argument. Two objects sit side by side, and the case for why they belong to
          the same idea sits underneath them. Sometimes that is a watch and a car.
          Other times it is the knife in your pocket, the bag on your shoulder, or the
          bike in the garage. The category was never the rule.
        </p>

        <p class="pullquote">Taste is the whole product.</p>

        <p>
          There are no photographs here, and that is a deliberate choice rather than an
          oversight. A photograph lets a pairing cheat, because two things can look
          good together and still mean nothing to each other. When you remove the
          image, the only thing holding a match together is the reason behind it. If
          that reason is weak, you will feel it immediately, and every pairing on this
          site has to pass that same test.
        </p>

        <p>
          A match works when both objects answer the same question in their own way,
          whether that answer is honesty, restraint, or a refusal to be more than they
          are. Sometimes that places an expensive machine next to something that costs
          less than dinner, and that is fine, because the price was never the
          connection.
        </p>

        <p>
          It begins with watches and cars because those are the two things I reach for
          first, but the rule was never about two categories. Anything you carry, and
          anything that carries you, can earn a place here, as long as the pairing
          holds up.
        </p>

        <p>
          You will disagree with some of these, and you are meant to. The comments are
          where the second half of the argument happens, so bring a better pairing if
          you have one.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .rule-title {
    font-family: var(--display);
    text-transform: uppercase;
    line-height: 0.92;
    letter-spacing: 0.006em;
    font-size: clamp(44px, 9vw, 104px);
    margin-top: 8px;
  }
</style>
